      "title": "Global Journal of Smart Contracts and Legal Innovation",
      "iconClass": "fa-industry",
      "articles": [
        {
          "title": "WTO Compatibility of Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanisms",
          "iconClass": "fa-balance-scale",
          "fullContent": "<p>This article assesses whether carbon border adjustment mechanisms (CBAMs) violate WTO non-discrimination principles (GATT Articles I and III). We argue that CBAMs can be justified under GATT Article XX (environmental exception) if designed to avoid arbitrary discrimination. The analysis draws on the EU's CBAM proposal and recent WTO rulings on environmental measures (e.g., Brazil–Retreaded Tyres).</p>"
        },
        {
          "title": "EU CBAM: Implementation Challenges and Trade Implications",
          "iconClass": "fa-globe-europe",
          "fullContent": "<p>We examine the practical implementation of the EU's Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism, including verification of embedded emissions and exemptions for developing countries. The article predicts trade disputes with China, Russia, and the US, and offers recommendations for multilateral coordination under the Paris Agreement.</p>"
        },
        {
          "title": "Developing Countries and Carbon Border Adjustments",
          "iconClass": "fa-leaf",
          "fullContent": "<p>This paper analyzes the impact of CBAMs on developing country exports, particularly in Africa and South Asia. Using computable general equilibrium models, we show that CBAMs could reduce GDP by up to 2% in carbon-intensive exporting nations. The article proposes compensation mechanisms and technical assistance.</p>"
        },
        {
          "title": "US FAIR Act: Legal Analysis and Trade Consequences",
          "iconClass": "fa-landmark",
          "fullContent": "<p>We analyze the proposed US Foreign Pollution Fee Act (FAIR Act), which would impose a carbon fee on imports from countries with weaker climate policies. The article compares the FAIR Act to the EU CBAM and assesses its WTO compatibility, concluding that both face legal challenges.</p>"
        },
        {
          "title": "GATT Article XX Climate Exceptions: Scope and Limits",
          "iconClass": "fa-file-contract",
          "fullContent": "<p>This article provides a detailed interpretation of GATT Article XX(b) and (g) as applied to climate measures. We review WTO case law (US–Gasoline, Brazil–Tyres) and argue that necessity and even-handedness requirements are surmountable with proper design. A model statute for climate border measures is provided.</p>"
        }
      ],
