      "articles": [
        {
          "title": "Climate Refugees: Gaps in the 1951 Refugee Convention",
          "iconClass": "fa-user-friends",
          "fullContent": "<p>This article analyzes why most climate migrants do not qualify as refugees under the 1951 Convention (lack of persecution). We examine proposals for a new protocol on climate displacement, drawing on the Kampala Convention and the Global Compact for Migration.</p>"
        },
        {
          "title": "Planned Relocation of Climate-Threatened Communities",
          "iconClass": "fa-map-marker-alt",
          "fullContent": "<p>We provide a legal framework for planned relocation of communities threatened by sea-level rise and extreme weather. Case studies from Fiji, Alaska, and Bangladesh illustrate best practices, including free prior informed consent (FPIC) and compensation.</p>"
        },
        {
          "title": "Regional Frameworks for Environmental Migration in Asia-Pacific",
          "iconClass": "fa-map",
          "fullContent": "<p>This paper assesses regional frameworks for environmental migration, including the ASEAN Declaration on Climate Displacement and the Pacific Resilience Partnership. We identify gaps in binding obligations and propose a regional treaty.</p>"
        },
        {
          "title": "Human Rights Obligations in Climate-Induced Displacement",
          "iconClass": "fa-hands-helping",
          "fullContent": "<p>We examine the human rights obligations of states towards internally displaced persons (IDPs) due to climate change, under the Guiding Principles on Internal Displacement. The article focuses on rights to housing, health, and non-discrimination.</p>"
        },
        {
          "title": "Non-Refoulement and Climate Threat: Emerging Jurisprudence",
          "iconClass": "fa-gavel",
          "fullContent": "<p>This article explores whether the principle of non-refoulement applies to climate threats. Recent decisions by the UN Human Rights Committee (Teitiota v. New Zealand) suggest that climate-related harm may qualify in extreme cases. We analyze the threshold for success.</p>"
        }
      ],
